      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# And now, the data part!\n",
        "Let's look at some data. The first thing we're going to do is add the 'pandas' package to our environment. Pandas is a common and useful package in python for dealing with tables, matrices, and other common data forms. If you're working locally, you might need to install the package :"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "eIxLZB8x7bl_"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "pip install name_of_package_here"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "B-r8mpKM-B_C",
        "outputId": "84c2405a-871d-4f75-c3bc-ce293a232c1e"
      },
      "execution_count": 32,
      "outputs": [
        {
          "output_type": "stream",
          "name": "stdout",
          "text": [
            "Requirement already satisfied: numpy in /usr/local/lib/python3.12/dist-packages (2.0.2)\n"
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "We already have pandas, so we can go right to importing it! Whenever you start up an environment, you'll need to add the package(s) you want to use."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3b9RbjwG-t1q"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# import pandas library as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "import pandas as pd"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "wO-50q2l7qd-"
      },
      "execution_count": 5,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "#Importing data from a csv file\n",
        "Often, you'd read a file off of a computer. The code below shows how to do this. If the file is not in the current directory, write the full path name. You can also read in specfic sheets of an excel file using xlrd:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "JzUwgcDF_GCi"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# function for reading files\n",
        "pd.read_csv(‘filename.csv’)\n",
        "pd.read_excel(‘filename.xlsx’)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "My-TIII98A5h"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "If you want to get your data out of the python environment and back into a .csv or .xlsx file, you can use the following, remembering to sub in the name of the variable before the .to_csv or .to_excel:"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "2A9cFeSo_jYk"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "# function for writing files. Let's pretend we're converting a variable called 'awesome_data':\n",
        "awesome_data.to_csv(‘filename.csv’)# remember your file extensions!\n",
        "awesome_data.to_excel(‘filename.xlsx’)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "gYAykwvB_mjN"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# And now, let's look at some data!\n",
        "This is a dataset from 2018 on Marvel and DC superhero movies. We have the following data:\n",
        "\n",
        "*   Title\n",
        "*   Studio (Marvel or DC)\n",
        "*   Year of release\n",
        "*   Tomatometer (Rotten Tomatoes critics' ratings)\n",
        "*   Popcorn meter (Rotten Tomatoes viewer ratings)\n",
        "*   Enjoyment (Participant ratings on a 1 (low)-10 (high) Likert scale)\n",
        "*   Fun (Participant ratings on a 1 (low)-7 (high) Likert scale)\n",
        "*   Silly (Participant ratings on a 1 (low)-7 (high) Likert scale)\n",
        "*   NChris (how many Hot Chrises are in this movie)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n"
